.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ztmux
is a terminal multiplexer: it lets a number of terminals be created,
accessed, and controlled from a single screen.
.B ztmux
may be detached from a screen and continue running in the background, then
later reattached.
.PP
It is a from-source port of
.BR tmux (1)
to Rust \(em the whole program (server, client, the grid and screen model,
the input parser, layouts, the command language, formats, and the terminal
back end), not a wrapper around the
.B tmux
binary and not control mode.
.PP
When
.B ztmux
is started it creates a new session with a single window and displays it on
screen. A status line at the bottom of the screen shows information on the
current session and is used to enter interactive commands.
.PP
A session is a single collection of pseudo terminals under the management of
.BR ztmux .
Each session has one or more windows linked to it. A window occupies the
entire screen and may be split into rectangular panes, each of which is a
separate pseudo terminal. Any number of
.B ztmux
instances may connect to the same session, and any number of windows may be
present in the same session.
.PP
.B ztmux
keeps its state in a single server process, which manages all the clients,
sessions, windows, and panes.
.SS Compatibility with tmux
.B ztmux
is a drop-in reimplementation and deliberately shares
.BR tmux (1)'s
runtime conventions so existing configuration and tooling keep working:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
the client and server speak tmux's wire protocol over a socket kept under
.IR $TMUX_TMPDIR / tmux- UID / (default
.IR /tmp/tmux- UID /);
.IP \(bu 2
configuration is read from the tmux search path (see
.B FILES
below), i.e.
.I ~/.tmux.conf
by default;
.IP \(bu 2
the server exports
.B $TMUX
to each pane, identifying the socket, session, and pane.
.RE
.PP
A running
.B ztmux
server is therefore reachable by any tmux-protocol client (including the
.B ztmux
binary itself, native GUI clients, and the standard
.BR tmux (1)
commands where compatible).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-2
Force
.B ztmux
to assume the terminal supports 256 colours.
.TP
.B \-C
Start in control mode. Given twice
.RB ( \-CC )
disables echo.
.TP
.B \-D
Do not start the server as a daemon; run it in the foreground.
.TP
.BR \-c " " \fIshell-command\fP
Execute
.I shell-command
using the default shell and exit.
.TP
.BR \-f " " \fIfile\fP
Specify an alternative configuration
.IR file .
.TP
.B \-l
Behave as a login shell.
.TP
.BR \-L " " \fIsocket-name\fP
Use a different
.I socket-name
under the
.B ztmux
socket directory rather than the default
.RB ( default ).
.TP
.B \-N
Do not start the server even if the command would normally do so.
.TP
.B \-q
Suppress the printing of "no server running" style informational messages
where applicable.
.TP
.BR \-S " " \fIsocket-path\fP
Specify a full alternative path to the server socket.
.TP
.BR \-T " " \fIfeatures\fP
Set terminal
.I features
for the client, as a comma-separated list.
.TP
.B \-u
Assume the terminal supports UTF-8.
.TP
.B \-V
Report the
.B ztmux
version and exit.
.TP
.B \-v
Request verbose logging. May be specified multiple times for more detail.
.PP
The remaining arguments,
.IR command " and " flags ,
select a tmux command (for example
.BR new-session ", " list-sessions ", or " split-window )
and its options. With no command,
.B ztmux
attaches to the most recently used session, creating one if none exists.
.SH EXTENSIONS
The following capabilities are original to
.B ztmux
and have no counterpart in upstream
.BR tmux (1).
They live in the extension layer of the code base and are held apart from the
ported core.
.SS Structured output
The listing commands
.BR list-sessions ", " list-windows ", " list-panes ", " list-clients ,
and
.B list-buffers
accept
.B \-o
.I format
to emit machine-readable output instead of a formatted text line:
.RS
.TP
.B json
A pretty-printed JSON array of objects, one per item, with numbers and
booleans typed natively and strings escaped.
.TP
.BR jsonl " (or " ndjson )
One JSON object per line (newline-delimited JSON), with no enclosing array.
.TP
.B csv
RFC 4180 comma-separated values with a header row.
.TP
.B tsv
Tab-separated values with a header row.
.TP
.B table
Human-readable, whitespace-aligned columns with a header and a rule.
.RE
.PP
Each format uses a stable, per-command field schema, driven by the same
.RB #{ ... }
format engine as the text output, so the
.B \-f
.I filter
option still applies. An unrecognised
.I format
is an error. For example:
.PP
.RS
.EX
ztmux list\-panes \-a \-o json
ztmux list\-sessions \-o table
.EE
.RE
.SS ztmux dashboard
.B ztmux dashboard
launches a live full-screen dashboard of the running server: a navigable
session\(->window\(->pane tree, a detail panel (a pane table for the selected
window, pane details for a selected pane, or session and client details for a
selected session), a live
.B capture-pane
preview of the selected pane, header counts, and a pane-count sparkline. It
refreshes once per second.
Keys:
.BR j / k " or " \(ua / \(da
move,
.BR g / G
jump to top/bottom,
.B Enter
focus the selection (attach the client to it),
.B r
refresh now,
.B x
kill the selection \(en session, window, or pane \(en (with confirmation),
.B ?
toggle help, and
.BR q " or " Escape
quit. The mouse wheel scrolls the tree and a left click selects the row under
the cursor.
It is a client subcommand that reads the server through the structured output
above and targets the socket selected by
.BR \-L / \-S .
.SS ztmux switch
.B ztmux switch
opens an interactive fuzzy picker over every session, window, and pane. Type
to filter (case-insensitive subsequence match); the selection is applied with
.BR switch-client ", " select-window ,
and
.B select-pane
on
.BR Enter ;
.B Escape
cancels.
.SS ztmux tree
.B ztmux tree
prints the whole server as a one-shot session\(->window\(->pane ASCII tree
(coloured when stdout is a terminal, plain when piped). It is built from the
same structured output and targets the socket selected by
.BR \-L / \-S .
.SS ztmux doctor
.B ztmux doctor
runs a one-shot health check of the build, the terminal environment
.RB ( TERM ,
terminfo, colour, locale), the resolved socket, the reachable server, and
resource limits. Output is a grouped, coloured report, or a machine-readable
object with
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json ).
The process exit status is the worst severity seen \(en 0 all ok, 1 warnings,
2 errors \(en so it drops into a CI gate. It is safe to run with no server up.
.SS ztmux stats
.B ztmux stats
prints a one-shot summary of the server: session/window/pane/client counts,
attached and dead counts, the busiest session, the largest window, the oldest
session, and a per-command histogram. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same figures as a machine-readable object.
.SS ztmux graph
.B ztmux graph
renders the session\(->window\(->pane tree as a diagram. Select the format with
.B \-o
.IR dot | mermaid | html
(default
.BR mermaid ):
Graphviz DOT, Mermaid, or a self-contained HTML page that draws the Mermaid
diagram. Useful for documentation and screenshots, e.g.
.RS
.EX
ztmux graph \-o dot | dot \-Tpng > tree.png
ztmux graph \-o html > tree.html
.EE
.RE
.SS ztmux watch
.B ztmux watch
is a top-like live monitor: a table of every pane's process with %CPU, %MEM,
RSS, and state (joined from
.BR ps ),
refreshed a few times a second and sortable by CPU, memory, or command.
Keys:
.BR j / k " or " \(ua / \(da
move,
.B s
cycle the sort,
.B r
refresh now, and
.BR q " or " Escape
quit.
.SS ztmux events
.B ztmux events
streams server lifecycle changes as newline-delimited JSON: session, window,
and pane created/closed/renamed, window layout changes, pane command changes and
deaths, and client attach/detach. It diffs successive snapshots, so a client can
subscribe to changes instead of re-polling.
.B \-n
.I ms
sets the poll interval (default 500) and
.B \-\-count
.I N
exits after N events. It runs until interrupted otherwise.
.SS ztmux ps
.B ztmux ps
prints a one-shot, pipeable table of every pane's process \(en pane id,
location, command, pid, %CPU, %MEM, RSS, and state (joined from
.BR ps ),
sorted by CPU. It is the non-interactive complement to
.BR "ztmux watch" .
With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits a JSON array.
.SS ztmux snapshot
.B ztmux snapshot
dumps the whole server as a single nested JSON document
(sessions \(-> windows \(-> panes, plus the client list) \(en a convenient
primitive for external tooling. It is read-only and is not a save/restore
format.
.SS ztmux prune
.B ztmux prune
finds and removes cleanup candidates: dead panes
.RB ( \-\-dead ),
window-less sessions
.RB ( \-\-empty ),
and detached sessions idle beyond a threshold
.RB ( \-\-idle
.IR seconds ).
With no selector, both
.B \-\-dead
and
.B \-\-empty
apply. It is
.B dry-run by default
(prints what it would remove); pass
.B \-f
or
.B \-\-force
to actually kill.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the plan as JSON.
.SS ztmux layout
.B ztmux layout
.I name
.RB [ \-t
.IR window ]
applies a named layout preset to a window: the five built-in tmux layouts
.RB ( even-h ", " even-v ", " main-h ", " main-v ", " tiled )
plus composite presets
.RB ( dev ", " ide ", " grid )
that create panes.
.B "ztmux layout list"
lists the presets. It is
.B dry-run by default
(prints the commands); pass
.B \-f
or
.B \-\-apply
to run them.
.SS ztmux find
.B ztmux find
.I query
searches every pane in the server and prints the ones whose command, current
path, title, or enclosing window name contains
.I query
(a case-insensitive substring match). Each row shows the pane id, its
.RI ( session : window . pane )
location, the command, which fields matched, and the path. It exits non-zero
when nothing matched, so it composes in shell
.B if
tests.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the matches as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux recent
.B ztmux recent
lists the sessions ranked by last activity, most-recently-active first, with a
compact relative age for both activity and creation time. It is the pipeable
"jump back to what I was last doing" primitive.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the rows as a JSON array (activity and creation kept as raw Unix
seconds).
.SS ztmux usage
.B ztmux usage
aggregates each pane's CPU%, memory%, and resident-set size by session and
prints one row per session, busiest (by CPU) first \(em the "which session is
eating the machine" view.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the rollup as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux grep
.B ztmux grep
.I pattern
captures every pane and prints the lines whose contents contain
.I pattern
(a case-insensitive substring), one
.RI ( location : line : " text)"
per match. Where
.B find
matches pane metadata,
.B grep
matches what is actually on the screen. By default only the visible screen is
searched; pass
.B \-a
or
.B \-\-history
to search the full scrollback. It exits non-zero when nothing matched.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the matches as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux peek
.B ztmux peek
captures the visible contents of every pane and prints each under a header
identifying it \(em the "show me every screen at once" view.
.B \-t
.I substr
limits the dump to panes whose
.RI ( session : window . pane )
location contains
.IR substr .
.B \-o
.I json
emits an array of
.RI { pane , location , command , content }
objects.
.SS ztmux bcast
.B ztmux bcast
.I command
sends
.I command
to every pane matching the filters \(em the cross-server generalisation of
.BR synchronize-panes .
.B \-c
.I substr
restricts to panes whose running command contains
.IR substr ;
.B \-s
.I session
restricts to one session; both may be combined. The command is sent literally
followed by Enter unless
.B \-N
or
.B \-\-no\-enter
is given. It is
.B dry-run by default
(prints the panes it would target); pass
.B \-f
or
.B \-\-force
to actually send.
.SS ztmux pstree
.B ztmux pstree
walks the OS process table and prints the full descendant process tree rooted
at each pane's process \(em the "what is actually running in here" view, where
.B ps
shows only the pane's own shell. A pane whose process has exited shows
.BR "(no process)" .
.B \-o
.I json
emits a nested JSON document per pane.
.SS ztmux ports
.B ztmux ports
lists every listening TCP socket and maps each back to the pane it runs under
by walking the process tree, answering "which pane is my dev server in". A
socket owned by no pane is still listed with a
.B \-
location. It degrades quietly to an empty table when
.BR lsof (8)
is unavailable.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux info
.B ztmux info
.I target
resolves
.I target
\(em a pane id
.RI ( %N ),
a
.RI ( session : window . pane )
location, or a session name \(em to one pane and prints everything the query
layer knows about it: identity and geometry, its process id/command and
CPU/memory/RSS, and the tail of its current screen.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same as one object.
.SS ztmux dedup
.B ztmux dedup
groups every live pane by its current working directory and running command and
prints only the groups with two or more members \(em the redundant panes you can
close. Where
.B prune
reclaims dead or empty objects and
.B find
searches metadata for a query,
.B dedup
computes the duplicate relation the others do not. Each group is given a stable
integer id so the flat table stays greppable; panes with no working directory
are skipped.
.B \-o
.I json
emits one object per group, each carrying its member panes.
.SS ztmux size
.B ztmux size
reports every live pane's
.IR width x height
and derived cell area, smallest area first, so the cramped panes sort to the top
\(em the "which pane is too small to work in" view.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux groups
.B ztmux groups
lists only the sessions that belong to a session group \(em sessions created
with
.B new\-session \-t
that share one set of windows \(em clustered by group then name, so members of
the same group sit together. It is the "which of my sessions are really the same
windows" view; ungrouped sessions are omitted.
.B \-o
.I json
emits one object per group, each carrying its member sessions.
.SS ztmux tty
.B ztmux tty
maps every live pane to its terminal device
.RI ( /dev/ttys NNN ),
sorted by location \(em the path you write to a pane directly or correlate with
.BR ps (1),
.BR w (1),
or
.BR lsof (8).
Dead panes are skipped.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux git
.B ztmux git
asks git about every live pane's working directory and prints one row per pane
that is inside a repository \(em its repo name, current branch (or short SHA
when detached), and whether the tree is dirty. It is the multi-repo, multi-pane
status board: "which pane is on which branch, and is it dirty." Panes outside a
repo are omitted; unique directories are resolved once. Rows are sorted by repo,
branch, then location.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux active
.B ztmux active
prints the focus point of every session \(em its active window and the active
pane inside it, with that pane's command and path. Where
.B tree
prints the whole structure,
.B active
is the one-line-per-session "where is focus, everywhere" jump map. Sorted by
session.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux ssh
.B ztmux ssh
scans the process table for
.B ssh
clients, parses each one's destination from its command line, and attributes it
to the pane it runs under \(em the map of every live remote session: "which pane
am I remoted into, and where." SSH processes under no pane are dropped. Rows are
sorted by location then target.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux disk
.B ztmux disk
runs
.BR df (1)
against every live pane's working directory and reports the filesystem, how full
it is, and how much is free \(em fullest first, the "which pane is on a disk
about to fill up" view. Unique directories are resolved once; panes with no
directory are omitted.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux net
.B ztmux net
lists every established outbound TCP connection and attributes it to the pane it
runs under \(em "what is this pane talking to." Where
.B ports
shows inbound listeners,
.B net
shows the live remote peers; connections under no pane are dropped so the table
stays the panes' own traffic. Rows are sorted by location then peer.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux env
.B ztmux env
compares every session's environment against the server's global environment
.RB ( show\-environment \~ \-g )
and prints only the variables that differ \(em the per-session overrides, the
"why does this session's shell behave differently" view. Rows are sorted by
session then variable.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux history
.B ztmux history
ranks every live pane by how many lines of scrollback it is holding, largest
first, with how full each is against its own
.B history\-limit
\(em the "which pane is hoarding scrollback" view, the off-screen counterpart to
.BR "ztmux size" .
Ties break by location.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux mode
.B ztmux mode
lists the panes that are currently in a mode (copy-mode, view-mode, or a
chooser) and which one \(em so a pane left paused, no longer showing live
output, is easy to find. Panes showing live output are omitted; rows are sorted
by location.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux zoom
.B ztmux zoom
lists the windows that currently have a zoomed pane and the pane each is zoomed
to \(em so a window left zoomed (hiding its other panes) is easy to find.
Windows in a normal split are omitted; rows are sorted by session then window.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux marks
.B ztmux marks
lists the marked pane \(em the one set with
.B select\-pane \-m
that
.BR join\-pane , swap\-pane ,
and
.B move\-pane
use as the implicit source. tmux keeps at most one mark, so this is normally
zero or one row.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux alerts
.B ztmux alerts
lists every window with a pending alert \(em a bell, activity (under
.BR monitor\-activity ),
or silence (under
.BR monitor\-silence ) \(em
and which alerts are pending on each, across the whole server without an
attached client. Windows with no alert are omitted; rows are sorted by session
then window.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux titles
.B ztmux titles
prints every live pane's advertised title \(em what the program inside set with
the terminal title escape or
.BR "select\-pane \-T" .
ssh and many shells push the current host or command into it, so it is the
complement to
.BR "ztmux ssh" .
Panes with an empty title are omitted; rows are sorted by location.
.B \-o
.I json
emits the same rows as a JSON array.
.SS ztmux equalize
.B ztmux equalize
re-lays every window that has more than one pane to a balanced layout, across
the whole server or one session with
.BR \-s .
The
.I layout
positional selects the target
.RB ( even\-horizontal ,
.BR even\-vertical ,
.BR main\-horizontal ,
.BR main\-vertical ,
or
.BR tiled ,
the default). Where
.B ztmux layout
applies a preset to one window, this sweeps them all. Like
.BR prune ,
it is dry-run by default and only applies with
.BR \-f / \-\-force .
.SS ztmux respawn
.B ztmux respawn
restarts every dead pane in place (running
.B respawn\-pane
on each), across the whole server or one session with
.BR \-s .
Where
.B prune
removes dead panes,
.B respawn
revives them. Like
.BR prune ,
it is dry-run by default and only acts with
.BR \-f / \-\-force .
.SS ztmux clear
.B ztmux clear
runs
.B clear\-history
on every pane that holds scrollback, across the whole server or one session with
.BR \-s ,
reclaiming that memory in one command. It is the write-side companion to
.BR "ztmux history" .
Panes with an empty buffer are skipped. Like
.BR prune ,
it is dry-run by default and only acts with
.BR \-f / \-\-force .
.SS ztmux retitle
.B ztmux retitle
sets each live pane's title (via
.BR "select\-pane \-T" )
to the command running in it, so
.B ztmux titles
and the status line show what each pane is doing. Only panes whose title differs
from their command are touched. Like
.BR prune ,
it is dry-run by default and only applies with
.BR \-f / \-\-force .
.SS ztmux cwd
.B ztmux cwd
groups every live pane by its working directory and ranks the directories by
pane count, busiest first \(en the "which directories am I working in, and how
many panes sit in each" view. Where
.B ztmux dedup
reports only the panes that collide on the pair
.RI ( path ", " command ),
.B cwd
lists every directory with its pane count and the distinct commands running
there.
.B $HOME
is abbreviated to
.B ~
for display. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the full path, the pane count, the distinct commands, and every pane
location as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux who
.B ztmux who
lists the clients attached to the server \(en the terminals looking at it right
now \(en with each client's tty, the session it is viewing, its screen size, its
.BR $TERM ,
and its pid. Clients are grouped by the session they view (a shared or remote
socket may carry several). With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux age
.B ztmux age
ranks sessions by their creation time, oldest first \(en the mirror image of
.BR "ztmux recent" ,
which ranks by last activity. It surfaces the long-lived sessions that have been
up the longest. A compact relative age is shown for the terminal; a session
whose creation time is unknown sorts last and renders as
.BR \- .
With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
the raw unix creation timestamp is emitted.
.SS ztmux cmd
.B ztmux cmd
counts how many live panes are running each command and ranks the commands by
that count, busiest first \(en the "what am I running, and how much of it" view.
Where
.B ztmux ps
prints one row per pane and
.B ztmux cwd
groups panes by directory,
.B cmd
collapses the server by command. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the command, the pane count, and every pane location as a
machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux dead
.B ztmux dead
reports every dead pane \(en a pane whose process exited while
.B remain-on-exit
kept it in place. Where
.B ztmux prune
reclaims dead panes and
.B ztmux respawn
revives them (both mutating),
.B dead
only lists them: the read-only inventory to look at before pruning or
respawning. Each row shows the pane, its location, the command that was running,
its last pid, and its working directory. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array; an empty server prints just
the header.
.SS ztmux layouts
.B ztmux layouts
reports the current layout string of every window \(en its pane count and the
raw tmux layout geometry that
.B select-layout
consumes. Where
.B ztmux layout
applies a named preset and
.B ztmux equalize
re-balances windows,
.B layouts
only reports, so it is the view to capture before changing a layout (to restore
it later) or to diff for windows that drifted off a preset. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux detached
.B ztmux detached
lists the sessions with no client attached \(en the ones running in the
background \(en ranked by last activity, freshest first. Where
.B ztmux recent
ranks every session and
.B ztmux age
ranks them by creation time,
.B detached
filters to the ones nobody is looking at, so the session you most likely want to
reattach sorts to the top and the stale ones you can safely kill sink to the
bottom. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
the raw unix timestamps are emitted; an all-attached server prints just the
header.
.SS ztmux density
.B ztmux density
ranks windows by how many panes they hold, most-split first \(en the companion
to
.B ztmux size
(which ranks individual panes by cell area) for spotting the window that has
grown unwieldy and wants a
.B break-pane
or a fresh layout. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux nested
.B ztmux nested
lists the panes whose foreground command is itself a terminal multiplexer
.RB ( tmux ", " ztmux ", " screen ", " zellij ", " byobu ", " dvtm ", " abduco ", " dtach ) \(en
a multiplexer running inside one of this server's own panes. It is matched on the
pane's
.B pane_current_command
so it catches a multiplexer started directly in a local pane; a remote
multiplexer reached over SSH shows up as
.B ssh
(see
.BR "ztmux ssh" )
rather than here. Nested multiplexers swallow the prefix key and confuse
.B send-keys
and
.BR capture-pane ,
so it helps to see exactly where they are. The command is matched exactly, so
.B tmuxinator
and
.B screenfetch
are not mistaken for the real thing. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array; a server with none prints
just the header.
.SS ztmux solo
.B ztmux solo
lists the windows that hold a single, unsplit pane \(en the complement of
.B ztmux density
(which ranks windows by how many panes they hold). These are the windows you
could split further or fold into another; each row also shows what the lone pane
is running, so it doubles as the "which windows are a single bare shell" view.
With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array; a server with no single-pane
windows prints just the header.
.SS ztmux shells
.B ztmux shells
lists the panes sitting at a bare shell prompt \(en a pane whose foreground
command is an interactive shell
.RB ( zsh ", " bash ", " fish ", " "\&..." )
is idle, so it is a pane you can drop into and reuse. Where
.B ztmux cmd
counts every command and
.B ztmux nested
isolates the multiplexer panes,
.B shells
isolates the free, at-prompt panes. It is matched on the pane's
.B pane_current_command
so a pane running a foreground job reports that job instead and correctly drops
out. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array; a server with no idle shells
prints just the header.
.SS ztmux fanout
.B ztmux fanout
ranks sessions by their total pane count across every window \(en pure
structure, with no resource probing. Where
.B ztmux density
ranks individual windows and
.B ztmux usage
ranks sessions by the CPU and memory they burn (reading
.IR /proc ),
.B fanout
answers "which session have I fanned out the most panes in" \(en a fast,
always-available structural size, where a session full of idle shells is large
even though it is light in
.BR usage .
With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux busy
.B ztmux busy
lists the live panes running a program rather than sitting idle at a prompt \(en
the exact complement of
.BR "ztmux shells" .
These are the panes with an editor, a build, an
.BR ssh ,
or a nested multiplexer in the foreground: the "where is work actually happening
right now" view. The two share a shell set, so
.B busy
and
.B shells
partition the live panes exactly. It is matched on the pane's
.BR pane_current_command .
With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array; a server where every pane is
idle prints just the header.
.SS ztmux focus
.B ztmux focus
reports the active pane of every window \(en the pane your cursor lands in when
you select that window. Where
.B ztmux active
reports focus once per session (the session's active window and its active
pane),
.B focus
reports it once per window, so you see the landing pane for every window, not
just the frontmost one \(en the "if I switch to window N, where do I end up" map.
Each row shows the window, the active pane, and what it is running. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux named
.B ztmux named
lists the windows whose name no longer tracks the running command. With
.B automatic-rename
on, a window's name mirrors its active pane's command; a window whose name
differs is one you have deliberately named (with
.B rename-window
or by turning automatic-rename off so a chosen name sticks). It is the "which
windows did I bother to name, and what did I call them" view \(en the navigation
map for
.BR "select-window -t <name>" .
Windows with an empty name, or whose name still equals the active command, are
omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux project
.B ztmux project
reports the project kind and root behind every pane's directory. For each live
pane it walks up from the working directory to the nearest project marker
.RB ( Cargo.toml ", " go.mod ", " package.json ", " pyproject.toml ", " Gemfile ", "
"\&..." , falling back to a bare
.BR .git )
and reports what kind of project the pane is sitting in and where its root is.
Where
.B ztmux git
answers branch and dirty state and
.B ztmux cwd
groups by raw directory,
.B project
answers what you are working
.I on
in each pane. It is filesystem-only \(en marker lookups, no subprocess \(en and
resolves each unique directory once. Panes not inside any recognised project are
omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array, sorted by kind, project,
then location.
.SS ztmux remote
.B ztmux remote
reports the git
.B origin
remote each pane's repository points at, in a compact
.I host/owner/repo
form. Where
.B ztmux git
reports the working-tree condition and
.B ztmux ahead
reports sync distance,
.B remote
answers which repository a pane is in \(en the identity \(en so a wall of panes
maps to the actual projects behind them. Panes outside a repo or with no
.B origin
are omitted, and each unique directory is resolved once. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows, including the raw URL, as a machine-readable array,
sorted by remote then location.
.SS ztmux ahead
.B ztmux ahead
reports how far each pane's repository is ahead of (unpushed) and behind
(unpulled) its upstream. For every live pane on a branch that tracks an upstream
it asks git for the ahead/behind counts and prints both, with the most
out-of-sync repositories first, so the ones needing a push or pull float to the
top. Panes outside a repo, or on a branch with no upstream, are omitted; each
unique directory is resolved once. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux changes
.B ztmux changes
counts the files with uncommitted edits in every pane's repository \(en the
.B git status --porcelain
line count \(en and ranks the repos by it, dirtiest first. Where
.B ztmux git
reports dirty state as a yes/no and
.B ztmux ahead
counts unpushed commits,
.B changes
reports how much unsaved work is sitting in each working tree, so you can see
where to commit next. Clean repositories and non-repo panes are omitted; each
unique directory is resolved once. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux stash
.B ztmux stash
reports the repositories that have entries in
.B git stash list
behind a pane, and how many \(en the shelved work that is easy to forget across
a wall of panes. Where
.B ztmux changes
counts uncommitted files and
.B ztmux ahead
counts unpushed commits,
.B stash
surfaces the third bucket of unfinished state: work you set aside and moved on
from. Repositories with no stashes and non-repo panes are omitted; rows are
sorted by stash count, most first. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux elapsed
.B ztmux elapsed
reports how long each pane's foreground process has been running, longest first
\(en the view that surfaces the three-hour build you forgot about or the
.B ssh
session open since this morning. Where
.B ztmux usage
ranks by CPU and memory (how hard a process is working),
.B elapsed
ranks by wall-clock age (how long it has been working). A single
.B ps
call covers every pid. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows, elapsed as raw seconds, as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux mem
.B ztmux mem
ranks every pane's process by resident set size, biggest first \(en the
RAM-focused board. Where
.B ztmux usage
aggregates memory per session and
.B ztmux ps
prints the whole process table sorted by CPU,
.B mem
is the single-metric ranking for "which pane is eating memory", the companion
to
.B ztmux size
(screen geometry) and
.B ztmux history
(scrollback). Process stats come from one shared
.B ps
call. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows, RSS in kilobytes, as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux state
.B ztmux state
lists the panes whose process is in an abnormal state \(en a zombie that was
never reaped, a process stopped by a signal, or one wedged in an uninterruptible
disk or kernel wait. Where
.B ztmux ps
prints every pane's process with its state mixed in,
.B state
isolates just the panes that need a look: the health filter. The leading
.B ps
state code is mapped to a readable label. Healthy panes (running or sleeping)
and panes with no process are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux commit
.B ztmux commit
reports the last commit in every pane's repository \(en the short SHA, how long
ago it landed, and its subject \(en most-recent commit first. Where
.B ztmux git
shows branch and dirty state,
.B ztmux ahead
shows unpushed commits, and
.B ztmux changes
shows uncommitted files,
.B commit
shows what was last done in each repo. Panes outside a repo are omitted; each
unique directory is resolved once. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows, commit time as raw unix seconds, as a machine-readable
array.
.SS ztmux linked
.B ztmux linked
reports the windows that live in more than one session at once. tmux's
.B link-window
lets a single window (the same
.BR @id )
appear under several session/index slots, where an edit in one is an edit in
all; that sharing is invisible in the normal tree.
.B linked
groups every window by its id and reports the ones present in two or more
sessions, with every place they show up, most-shared first. It is built purely
from the server snapshot. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array; a server with no linked
windows prints just the header.
.SS ztmux conflicts
.B ztmux conflicts
counts the unmerged paths \(en the files a merge, rebase, or cherry-pick left in
conflict \(en in every pane's repository, and reports only the repos that have
any. Where
.B ztmux changes
counts all uncommitted files,
.B conflicts
isolates the subset that blocks progress: the repo is mid-operation and needs a
resolution first. Repos with no conflicts and non-repo panes are omitted; rows
are sorted by conflict count, most first. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux user
.B ztmux user
reports the user each pane's foreground process runs as, grouped by user. On a
single-user box this is uniform, but on a shared host or a server it answers who
is running what and where, and it catches the pane left in a
.B sudo
or
.B root
shell among your own. Where
.B ztmux ps
prints CPU and memory and
.B ztmux elapsed
prints runtime,
.B user
prints ownership. One
.B ps
call covers every pid. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux tag
.B ztmux tag
runs
.B git describe --tags
in every pane's repository and reports the result: the nearest tag and how many
commits the checkout is past it (for example
.IR v1.2.3-4-gabc123 ,
four commits beyond
.IR v1.2.3 ).
Where
.B ztmux commit
shows the last commit and
.B ztmux ahead
shows distance from upstream,
.B tag
shows distance from the last release. A checkout sitting exactly on a tag is
flagged. Repositories with no reachable tag, and non-repo panes, are omitted;
each unique directory is resolved once. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux vcs
.B ztmux vcs
reports which version-control system each pane's directory is under, by walking
up to the nearest marker
.RB ( .git ", " .hg ", " .svn ", " .jj ", " "\&..." ).
Where
.B ztmux git
and its siblings assume git,
.B vcs
answers the prior question \(en is this a checkout, and of what \(en so a
polyglot tree with a Mercurial repo here and a Subversion checkout there names
each. It is filesystem-only and resolves each unique directory once. Panes under
no recognised VCS are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux gone
.B ztmux gone
finds the live panes whose working directory no longer exists on disk \(en
deleted, renamed, or unmounted out from under them, so new commands fail for no
obvious reason. Where
.B ztmux cwd
groups panes by directory and
.B ztmux dead
lists dead processes,
.B gone
flags a live pane in a dead place, so you can
.B cd
it somewhere real. It is filesystem-only and checks each unique directory once. A
server whose panes are all in real directories prints just the header. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux buffers
.B ztmux buffers
lists the server's paste buffers \(en everything copied in copy-mode or loaded
with
.BR set-buffer / load-buffer \(en
with each buffer's size and a one-line preview of its contents, largest first.
The normal views never show the paste stack;
.B buffers
does, so you can see what you have before pasting. It reads the same
.B list-buffers -o json
output the port already emits. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows (full sample retained) as a machine-readable array; a
server with no buffers prints just the header.
.SS ztmux worktree
.B ztmux worktree
finds the panes sitting in a linked git worktree \(en a side checkout created by
.B git worktree add
that shares history with a main repo elsewhere. For each pane in a repo it
compares the worktree's git-dir against the shared common git-dir; they differ
only for a linked worktree. Where
.B ztmux git
reports branch and dirty state,
.B worktree
answers which panes are in a side checkout rather than the main tree. The main
worktree, submodules, and non-repo panes are omitted; each unique directory is
resolved once. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux submodules
.B ztmux submodules
runs
.B git submodule status
in every pane's repository and reports the repos that have submodules, with a
count of how many are out of sync \(en not initialised, or checked out at a
different commit than the superproject records. Where
.B ztmux changes
and
.B ztmux ahead
describe the superproject's own state,
.B submodules
describes its dependencies: the nested checkouts that quietly drift and break a
build. Repos with no submodules and non-repo panes are omitted; those with drift
sort first. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux term
.B ztmux term
aggregates the attached clients by
.BR $TERM :
how many are on
.IR screen-256color ,
how many on
.IR xterm-256color ,
and so on. Where
.B ztmux who
lists each client individually,
.B term
is the histogram \(en the client-side companion to
.B ztmux cmd
\(en useful when a capability bug only shows up on one terminal type and you need
to know who is on it. Ordered most-common first. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux start
.B ztmux start
reports the full command line each pane's root process was launched with \(en
its
.BR pane_pid \(en
as opposed to
.BR pane_current_command ,
the foreground name shown everywhere else. For a shell pane that is the shell
invocation; for a pane started with
.B new-window 'ssh host'
it is that whole command with its arguments, which the foreground name loses. One
.B ps
call covers every pid. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux writable
.B ztmux writable
finds the panes whose working directory exists but is read-only to you \(en a
root-owned tree, a read-only mount, someone else's checkout \(en where the first
write fails for a reason the prompt does not show. It checks each directory with
.BR access (2).
Where
.B ztmux gone
flags a directory that is
.IR missing ,
.B writable
flags one that is present but read-only. It is filesystem-only and checks each
unique directory once. A server whose panes can all write prints just the header.
With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux sync
.B ztmux sync
lists the windows that have
.B synchronize-panes
turned on \(en where every keystroke goes to all panes at once. That is powerful
for driving a fleet and dangerous when forgotten, and nothing in the normal views
shows it, so
.B sync
is the safety check before you type. It reads the
.B pane_synchronized
flag for every window and reports the ones where it is set. Windows without it are
omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux piped
.B ztmux piped
lists the panes with an active
.B pipe-pane
capture \(en output teed to a shell command for logging, monitoring, or
mirroring. A running pipe is invisible: the pane looks ordinary while everything
it prints also goes elsewhere.
.B piped
reads the
.B pane_pipe
flag and reports the panes where a pipe is active \(en the "what am I still
logging" check. Panes with no pipe are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux input
.B ztmux input
lists the panes that are ignoring keyboard input \(en a read-only observer, or a
pane a script left with input turned off, so it shows output but silently drops
every keystroke.
.B input
reads the
.B pane_input_off
flag and reports the panes where input is disabled \(en the "why won't this pane
take my typing" check. Panes accepting input are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux monitor
.B ztmux monitor
lists the windows armed to alert on themselves:
.B monitor-activity
raises an alert on any output,
.B monitor-silence
after N seconds of none. Where
.B ztmux alerts
shows the windows that have already fired,
.B monitor
shows the ones armed to fire \(en the standing watches you set and may have
forgotten. The always-on-by-default bell monitor is left out, as it would match
nearly every window. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux remain
.B ztmux remain
lists the windows with
.B remain-on-exit
set, where a pane whose process exits is held open as a dead pane rather than
closed
.RB ( on
always,
.B failed
only on a non-zero exit). Where
.B ztmux dead
lists the panes that have already died and
.B ztmux respawn
revives them,
.B remain
shows which windows are configured to hold their dead panes in the first place.
Windows with the default
.RB ( off )
are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux autoname
.B ztmux autoname
lists the windows whose name is pinned \(en
.B automatic-rename
turned off, so the name stays whatever you set no matter what runs there. Where
.B ztmux named
infers intent by comparing a window's name to its command,
.B autoname
reads the option directly, so it also catches a pinned name that happens to match
the command right now. Windows with the default (auto-rename on) are omitted.
With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux readonly
.B ztmux readonly
lists the clients attached in read-only mode \(en with
.B attach -r
or
.BR "switch-client -r" \(en
which can see a session but not type into it. Nothing in the normal views
distinguishes an observer from a live client. Where
.B ztmux who
lists every client,
.B readonly
isolates the view-only ones. Clients that can type are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux idle
.B ztmux idle
ranks the attached clients by how long since each last did anything \(en a
keystroke, a resize, a command \(en most-idle first: the connection someone
walked away from, the forgotten
.B attach
on another machine. Where
.B ztmux who
lists the clients and
.B ztmux readonly
flags the observers,
.B idle
sorts them by staleness. A compact relative age is shown for the terminal; with
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
the raw unix activity timestamp and idle seconds are emitted.
.SS ztmux viewers
.B ztmux viewers
counts the clients attached to each session and ranks the sessions by that count,
most-watched first \(en a paired session, a remote observer, the same session
open from two machines. Where
.B ztmux who
lists the clients individually and
.B ztmux fanout
ranks sessions by pane count,
.B viewers
ranks them by eyes on them. Sessions with no client attached do not appear. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux connected
.B ztmux connected
ranks the attached clients by how long they have been connected, longest first
\(en the
.B attach
left open on a server for days, the paired session joined this morning. Where
.B ztmux idle
ranks by time since last activity (staleness of use),
.B connected
ranks by time since attach (age of the connection) \(en two different questions
about the same client. A compact relative age is shown for the terminal; with
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
the raw unix attach timestamp and uptime seconds are emitted.
.SS ztmux constrain
.B ztmux constrain
ranks the attached clients by screen size, smallest first. When several clients
share a session the smallest one caps what everyone sees \(en with the default
.BR "window-size smallest" ,
the session is sized to the narrowest and shortest attached client \(en so the
top row is the client holding a session down. Where
.B ztmux who
lists every client and
.B ztmux viewers
counts them per session,
.B constrain
surfaces the size cap. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows, with width and height, as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux hooks
.B ztmux hooks
lists the command hooks configured on each session \(en a command bound to run
when something happens (a window is selected, a pane dies, a client attaches).
Hooks are invisible until they fire and easy to forget. For every session
.B hooks
reads the session-scope hooks (the ones you set, not the built-in global
defaults) and reports the event each is bound to and the command it runs \(en the
"what automation is wired into this server" view. Sessions with no custom hook
contribute nothing. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array, sorted by session then event.
.SS ztmux destroy
.B ztmux destroy
reports the sessions with
.B destroy-unattached
set \(en removed the moment the last client detaches. Handy for throwaway or
popup sessions, dangerous when forgotten. Where
.B ztmux detached
lists the sessions currently without a client,
.B destroy
warns which ones will not survive losing theirs. Sessions with the default
.RB ( off )
are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux status
.B ztmux status
reports the sessions with the status line turned off
.RB ( "set-option status off" ) \(en
a full-height view where it is easy to forget the tabs are hidden. It is a small
awareness view for a per-session display setting that nothing else surfaces.
Sessions showing the status line (the default) are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux keys
.B ztmux keys
summarises the key bindings by table. tmux groups bindings into tables \(en
.B root
(no prefix),
.B prefix
(after the prefix key),
.BR copy-mode / copy-mode-vi ,
and any custom tables created with
.BR "bind-key -T" .
A raw
.B list-keys
dumps hundreds of bindings at once;
.B keys
collapses that into one row per table with its binding count, busiest first,
surfacing how heavily each table is customised and which custom tables exist at
all. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux limit
.B ztmux limit
reports each session's
.B history-limit
\(en the maximum number of lines a pane keeps in its scrollback \(en ranked
largest first. Where
.B ztmux history
ranks panes by the scrollback they are using right now,
.B limit
reports the configured cap behind that usage, surfacing the sessions with an
unusually large (memory-hungry) or small (truncating) buffer. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux winsize
.B ztmux winsize
reports the windows whose
.B window-size
differs from the global default \(en
.BR latest ,
.BR largest ,
.BR smallest ,
or
.B manual
sizing when clients of different sizes are attached. Most windows inherit the
default;
.B winsize
lists the ones you have deliberately given a different rule. Where
.B ztmux constrain
shows which client caps a session,
.B winsize
shows which windows opt out of the default sizing. Windows on the default are
omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux borders
.B ztmux borders
reports the windows with
.B pane-border-status
enabled \(en a one-line label drawn on each pane's border
.RB ( top " or " bottom ),
usually the pane's title or command, so a split window self-documents which pane
is which. It is off by default;
.B borders
lists the windows where it is on and on which edge. Windows with the default
.RB ( off )
are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux lock
.B ztmux lock
reports the sessions with
.B lock-after-time
set \(en which lock their screen (running
.BR lock-command )
after that many seconds with no input, a small security measure for a session
left on a shared or unattended machine. It is off by default and easy to forget.
.B lock
lists the armed sessions and after how long, soonest-locking first. Sessions with
no lock timeout are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows, timeout in seconds, as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux titlebar
.B ztmux titlebar
reports the sessions with
.B set-titles
on \(en which update the outer terminal emulator's window or tab title to reflect
the active session, window, and pane. It is off by default. Where
.B ztmux titles
shows each pane's own title and
.B ztmux named
shows window names,
.B titlebar
is about the setting that projects those out to the host terminal. Sessions with
the default (off) are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS ztmux visual
.B ztmux visual
reports the sessions that show alerts visually \(en
.BR visual-bell ,
.BR visual-activity ,
and
.B visual-silence
put a message on the status line rather than (or as well as) passing a terminal
bell through. Where
.B ztmux monitor
shows which windows are armed to alert and
.B ztmux alerts
shows which have fired,
.B visual
shows how a session presents an alert when it fires, and which of the three it
applies to. Sessions using the default (bell-only) are omitted. With
.B \-o
.I json
(or
.BR \-\-json )
it emits the same rows as a machine-readable array.
.SS Default key bindings
For convenience each extension is also bound under the prefix key (these
bindings are original to
.B ztmux
and are added on top of the ported
.BR tmux (1)
defaults, which stay unchanged):
.RS
.TP
.B prefix C\-d
open the dashboard
.TP
.B prefix S
open the interactive picker
.TP
.B prefix T
show the server tree
.TP
.B prefix H
run the health check
.TP
.B prefix W
open the live process monitor
.TP
.B prefix I
show the stats report
.TP
.B prefix G
show the tree diagram
.RE
.PP
Each opens the tool in a
.B display\-popup
pointed at the current server, so they work from any attached client. The
streaming
.B events
subcommand runs until interrupted and is pipe oriented, so it is not bound by
default.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B TMUX
Set by the server for each pane to identify the socket, session, and pane of
the client.
.TP
.B TMUX_TMPDIR
Directory under which the per-user socket directory
.RI ( tmux- UID )
is created; defaults to
.IR /tmp .
.TP
.B TMUX_CONF
Colon-separated list of configuration file paths overriding the default
search path.
.TP
.B EDITOR
.TQ
.B VISUAL
Used to select the editor for interactive editing.
.SH FILES
.TP
.IR $TMUX_TMPDIR /tmux- UID /
The directory holding
.B ztmux
server sockets for the user
.IR UID ;
by default
.IR /tmp/tmux- UID / .
The default socket is named
.IR default .
.TP
.I ~/.tmux.conf
Default per-user configuration file. The full default search path is
.IR /etc/tmux.conf ,
.IR ~/.tmux.conf ,
.IR $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/tmux/tmux.conf ,
and
.IR ~/.config/tmux/tmux.conf .
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR tmux (1)
.PP
The upstream
.BR tmux (1)
sources are vendored under
.I vendor/tmux
in the ztmux repository as the reference this port is validated against, and a
parity suite checks
.B ztmux
output byte-for-byte against them.
